</li></ul></li><li id="tree_64770928" class="comment full contain"><span class="ind"></span>
<div id="comment_status_64770928" class="commentstatus"></div>
<div id="comment_64770928" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_64770928" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a rel="nofollow" id="comment_link_64770928" name="comment_link_64770928" href="//news.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23447136&amp;cid=64770928" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64770928)" >economics</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64770928" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64770928); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>3</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~sfcat">sfcat</a>  <span class="uid"><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~sfcat">( 872532 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64770928">		
		on Saturday September 07, 2024 @05:12PM (<span class="ind"></span><a rel="nofollow" href="//news.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23447136&amp;cid=64770928">#64770928</a>)
		<small> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64770928">This is really about economics.  When FOSS first came about, the idea was that developers supported themselves via consulting work associated with FOSS software.  That never happened.  So when companies with actual functioning business models started using FOSS, many people declared that a win since some FOSS devs got jobs with those companies.  However, then the cloud came about and it was possible for FOSS orgs to publish official containers and get revenue that way.  Its an actual FOSS business model that works.  But that gets ignored for some reason by these folks (since they didn't have any part in making that happen).  You also have to realize that Stallman and a few others are on lifetime grants like the Genius grant and so have no real first hand experience with what's its like to actually have to earn money.  This entire take seems very out of touch.  If you make a FOSS framework that is popular enough, the devs can actually have a salary and a living now if they can get customers to use their containers.  And making those containers secure and having them work with other popular software (which might be closed source) is required to make that happen.  Sooooo, that's a problem now?  I don't really understand.  I think these folks are just upset they don't get as much attention anymore because their licenses don't work for OpenSource projects in the cloud.  Either way, there are more devs able to support themselves via OpenSource software than ever before.  But since FSF isn't getting the donations anymore (they go directly to the devs instead of the lawyers at Apache or FSF), somehow this is a problem?</div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64770928">
<span class="ind"></span><a id="reply_link_64770928" class="btn link" href="//news.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23447136&amp;op=Reply&amp;threshold=1&amp;commentsort=0&amp;mode=thread&amp;pid=64770928" onclick="D2.replyTo(64770928); return false;">Reply to This</a> 	<a rel="nofollow" href="#" class="comment_share_toggle btn link">Share</a>
