		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64770992">Veteran of multiple Apache projects here. The key problem with OSS is lack of participation. I is hard to maintain complex software such as Drill, Impala, Druid and the like. Most users don't have the skills or time. Sometimes it falls to the sponsor company to do the work. It is understandable that the investors of that sponsor company want some ROI: turning proprietary seems reasonable. For FOSS to flourish, it must be something that encourages wide contribution, not just wide usage. The other end of the spectrum seems to be projects small enough that one enthusiastic person an run the whole show. Otherwise, as someone noted, its a "something-for-nothing" gig that turns OSS developers into suckers.

Also, I seldom found a hiring manager that even cared about my Apache contributions: they still wanted to know if I could do some silly coding exercise and never looked at the public complex PRs. (One company explained that I could have hired someone to do the work for me.)</div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64770992">
